title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W SW99c with four magazines (clone of Walther P99 compact)
location: Near I-10 and North Monroe, Tallahassee, Florida
postcontent:
---------
PRICE: $500
LOCATION: TALLAHASSEE
INCLUDED: Firearm, one 15-round P99 magazine with Walther P99 factory grip extension/sleeve, three 10-round S&W compact magazines (one with pinky extension), zippered handgun sleeve.
AVAILABLE EXTRA (right of first refusal given to buyer):  Gould and Goodrich Level 3 basketweave leather duty holster.
---------

The SW99 was a collaboration between Smith & Wesson and Walther, effectively "cloning" the Walther P99. Walther produced the frame, and Smith & Wesson produced the barrel and slide. It's identical to the P99 in structure and function, the only differences being aesthetics (primarily the lines on the slide and the rounded instead of squared trigger guard).

This particular model comes with the AS (Anti-Stress) trigger, which is unique in and of itself. When the striker is pre-cocked, the trigger has a pre-travel is taken up completely (and locked in place) when you pull the trigger to that point (without passing the break). From that point, the trigger pull is a crisp 4.5 pounds, with a very short reset. However, it can be carried in DA/SA mode with a pull weight of 7.8 pounds on the first pull by using the manual decocker.

Another distinct advantage is mag availability. It's fully compatible with magazines for the P99 as well as the PPQ M1 (just not M2, which are more expensive anyway), and Walther even makes a factory 20-round magazine for it. But unlike the Walther and it's 1-year warranty, S&W honors the warranty for the life of the firearm, not just the owner. It's perhaps for this reason the 9mm version is becoming harder and harder to find.

If you have any questions about it, I'd be happy to answer them. As you can certainly tell, I'm a dork about these things.

title: For Sale:  .38 AMU Brass
postcontent:
Brass from a .38 AMU cartridge. This listing is for fifty (50) empty brass. I have plenty more if you need more at the same price. These were stored away long ago and we just found them while cleaning out the basement.

Long Story:
Back in the late 50's and early 60's the Army Advanced Marksmanship Unit ( now known as the Army Marksmanship or AMU) was concerned with the major problem of proper functioning of the rimmed .38 Special cartridge through converted 1911 pistols. The major problem was feeding-there was a noticeable difference in the position of rounds in the magazine between the first and last rounds. To overcome this problem magazines were modified, feed ramps were polished, and the chambers enlarged to allow the cartridge to ride up the ramp and into the oversized chamber. This oversized chamber caused problems with accuracy.

To alleviate the feed problems Herman Gano, an AMU gunsmith came up with the ideal of the .38 AMU cartridge. The .38 AMU is basically a .38 Special with a semi-rimmed base, like the .38 Super. When used in appropriate guns, nearly all the feeding problems were eliminated. The first cases were hand made by turning down a .38 Special case in a lathe to remove the rim and form an extraction groove. Later the Army contracted Federal, Winchester-Western and Remington to produce the .38 AMU cartridge.

Colt Industries followed through by producing a conversion kit to be fitted on both the 1911 and Colt .38 Super pistols. The conversion kit consisted of a .38 AMU slide with all the innards, recoil spring, magazine, barrel bushing and a .38 AMU barrel. One interesting note, other than ID markings, there's no difference between the .38 AMU and .38 Super slide. The barrel is unique in that it had only one forward locking lug so the gun wouldn't lock up too tightly and hinder proper cycling with midrange ammo. The work required to "convert" a pistol to .38 AMU is approximately the same as a full accuracy job. The slide must be fitted to the frame, the barrel must be fitted to the slide, and the barrel lug fitted so it cams with the slide stop pin. 

.38 AMU never really took to the shooting crowd for several reasons. There were no empties available for reloading, (most shooters were geared for .38 Special), the conversion kits were somewhat difficult to install by the shooter, the advent of the .38 Special Gold Cup magazine which solved the feeding problem with regular .38 Special wadcutters, and the introduction of the Smith and Wesson 52, an out of the box match gun.

According to the SN, it was produced in 1974 (“The SKS Carbine”, S. Kehaya and J. Poyer). title: For Sale:  STEYR MA-91
postcontent:
For sale is my lightly used Steyr M9-A1 9MM pistol. This is a later model, with a roller bearing in the striker channel for a smoother and more consistent trigger pull. It is in excellent condition, and included are two 17 rd. magazines, the original case & papers, and keys for the built-in trigger lock. 

The Steyr has a similar grip angle, but a smaller diameter and much more ergomonic grip shape than the Glock 19. The Steyr has a 4mm lower bore axis, for less muzzle flip and less perceived recoil. The Steyr has a steel frame incorporating longer frame rails and the trigger / sear mechanism (very solid and precise). This steel frame fits into the polymer grip as a module. The glock uses its polymer grip as a frame to locate & hold the trigger mechanism, and the shorter frame rails are molded into the polymer grip. The Steyr uses unique fast acquisition trapezoidal / triangle combat sights which are made of steel (easily replaced if you prefer standard rectangular or night sights). The glock has plastic sights. The Steyr has a shorter trigger pull, with a quicker reset. The Steyr has a two round greater standard magazine capacity (17 rds versus 15). The Steyr has a built-in keyed trigger lock as an additional safety feature. The Steyr was initially designed for the .40 S&W, and then adapted for the less powerful 9mm. The Steyr's barrel has a fully supported chamber, and standard rifling to allow use of non-jacketed bullets, while the glock's chamber is not fully supported, and their rifling requires jacketed bullets.

Asking $525 but willing to listen to fair offers.
